english:
  title: A Letter of Gratitude Upon Taking Office in Nanyang
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I, Do-jeon, have received the gracious appointment as Governor of Nanyang and arrived at my post on the seventeenth day of this month. Receiving the royal decree with reverence, I depart to guard these distant territories, my heart trembling between shame and gratitude, uncertain how to compose myself.

    I reflect humbly that I, a man of no consequence, possessed no particular talent, yet through the late King's recognition, I was elevated to serve at court. When the traitor Shin Don fell and we made our report at the Royal Tomb, His Majesty entrusted me to study the musical scales and master the protocols of ancestral rites. When all ceremonies were completed without fault, the late King praised my efforts and appointed me to oversee ritual affairs while also managing the Seal Office and serving as Drafter of Edicts. Such was the depth of his grace.

    After the late King departed from us, I undertook my duties in the protocols, receiving commands from the court to gather the hundred officials and establish the great work. When Your Highness ascended the throne, you renewed all the affairs of state and appointed me to positions in the National Academy and as Drafter of Edicts. Honored with your summons, I entered the Royal Lecture Hall to expound upon the Great Learning, speaking earnestly of how the profound virtue of the Sage King reaches its culmination in reverence—how the ruler finds his limit in benevolence, the minister in respect, the father in compassion, the son in filial piety, and in dealings with others in faithfulness. Your Highness received these teachings with favor.

    Filled with gratitude for your recognition, I spoke without restraint, offended those in power, and was banished to the southern frontier. For nearly three years I endured the miasmic heat, nearly perishing. By law I was then removed to the countryside, and after four more years, you graciously allowed me to settle where circumstances suited me. Thus did Your Highness grant me a second life. Content in my humble retirement, I wished to become one of the forgotten worthies of this flourishing age.

    In the year Jiazi, Your Highness commanded Minister of State Jung Mong-ju to lead congratulations to the Ming on their sovereign's birthday. I served as the chief scribe, bearing our memorial to the Ming capital. Before my departure, two or three previous envoys had been detained, their fate unknown. The ministers at court were reluctant to venture forth, but following Minister Jung, I accepted the commission and departed without delay. I reached Nanjing and accomplished our mission, whereupon the detained envoys were released. This success came from Your Highness's sincere deference to the greater power and the diligent service of all the ministers—what achievement of mine could this be?

    Upon my return, I was immediately appointed Chief Sacrificer of the National Academy and Drafter of Edicts. When Your Highness sought the Ming's ratification of your succession, you entrusted me to compose the memorial, and when the imperial edict arrived, you had me master its reception ceremonies. The Ming Emperor commended the sincerity of our words, and the envoys likewise praised our propriety. Yet now that governance flourishes and virtuous scholars abound, how can I alone deserve such honor? This too is Your Highness's gift of immortal grace.

    The Bureau of Archives is the successor to the Imperial Library, where books and records reside under heavy responsibility for their preservation. Deeming me learned, you have placed me in this office—surely the height of a scholar's honor. Yet I am troubled by my meager talents in sustenance and my many dependents. Thus I sought an external appointment to complete my remaining years. Unexpectedly, the more I sought retirement, the higher my rank ascended; the more I declined honors, the greater your favor became.

    This is because Your Highness, with loyalty and sincerity, regards the circumstances of your servants and understands that my heart harbors no other intention. I dare not cease my humble efforts, but shall labor to illuminate your benevolent will, bringing peace to the exhausted people, and thereby repay even the smallest fraction of your boundless grace.
  footnotes:
    - Shin Don (辛旽) was a powerful eunuch and regent during the Goryeo period whose execution marked a turning point in Korean history.
    - The 'Great Learning' (大學) is one of the Four Books of Confucianism, foundational to Korean Neo-Confucian education.
    - The Ming court's recognition of the new Korean regime was politically crucial for its legitimacy.
    - Jung Do-jeon's banishment and later rehabilitation reflect the political turbulence of the founding of the Joseon Dynasty.
